      "side": 1,
      "message": "This patch does fundamentally different — and contradictory — things in `vars/pluginPipeline.groovy` and in `jenkins/gerrit-bazel-build-plugin*.sh`, under one commit message. They cannot both be right.\n\nThe Groovy change (correct): only `external_plugin_deps.MODULE.bazel` is aggregated across plugins, via `include(\"//plugins/\u003cname\u003e:external_plugin_deps.MODULE.bazel\")` append. `external_plugin_deps.bzl` and `external_package.json` are deliberately left as primary-only symlinks because those formats have no merge mechanism.\n\nThe bash change (wrong on all three counts):\n\n1. `setExternalDepsLinks` at line 24 lumps all three file formats together and calls it for every extra in the loop. It uses cp -f to a single fixed destination, so each iteration overwrites the previous.\n2. For `MODULE.bazel`: last-extra-wins instead of `include()` aggregation — does not solve the multi-plugin problem this commit claims to fix, and the bash pipeline still behaves as if only one plugin\u0027s `MODULE.bazel` exists.\n3. For `external_plugin_deps.bzl` and `external_package.json`: actively regresses correct previous behavior. Before this change, only the primary plugin\u0027s `.bzl` / `package.json` were ever placed in plugins/. Now any extra that ships either file overwrites the primary\u0027s — silently breaking builds that previously worked.\n\nI think what you want is for the bash function to mirror the Groovy logic — only `external_plugin_deps.MODULE.bazel` participates in the loop, and via echo `\u0027include(...)\u0027 \u003e\u003e` and not `cp -f`. The `external_plugin_deps.bzl` and `external_package.json` handling must stay outside the loop, scoped to the primary plugin only.",
